                            <comment id="16615581" author="paulk" created="Sat, 15 Sep 2018 03:13:42 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I originally marked methods with @Generated but the requirements for coverage/Jacoco are different to the methods we currently mark as synthetic, so instead I have created a new @Internal annotation.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;These methods are no longer synthetic normally but are instead marked @Internal. There was a condition where we didn&apos;t add @Internal due to an NPE that would occur in that scenario - I believe that would normally only occur when creating AST fragments which we do for some of our unit tests. But since I am unsure what some AST transformations might do, I left that condition in and for that case I leave the methods as synthetic.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;there is some code when using the metaclass mixin capability which used to skip synthetic methods. It now skips also @Internal methods. We&apos;ll need to see whether we need to make that condition more specific.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16620525" author="paulk" created="Wed, 19 Sep 2018 12:40:48 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;HEADSUP: I am likely to reopen this issue and defer for one more minor version. The current fix added @Internal and removed synthetic all in one go. This forces other libraries/tools which sneak into the more private areas of the language like Spock and possibly others to have to upgrade immediately. Instead I plan to keep the @Internal annotation as per the current solution but leave the methods as synthetic for at least one more version. This gives us times to get all the libraries/tools updated. I am also testing a few other libraries. I&apos;ll also write an email to the dev mailing list summarising this once I finish more testing.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16621173" author="daniel_sun" created="Wed, 19 Sep 2018 20:38:32 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;+1&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16645934" author="paulk" created="Thu, 11 Oct 2018 04:00:19 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Resolving just for 3.0 for now. We can add a 2.5.x fix version if/when we backport to 2_5_X.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
